1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Every conference venue has screens.

2
00:00:07,300 --> 00:00:09,300
Lobby displays.

3
00:00:09,600 --> 00:00:11,600
Corridor monitors.

4
00:00:11,900 --> 00:00:15,650
The big screen at the back of the main hall.

5
00:00:15,950 --> 00:00:19,700
Right now, most of those screens are showing a static

6
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:23,375
PowerPoint slide someone emailed to AV three days ago.

7
00:00:23,675 --> 00:00:27,425
With CueDeck's signage system, every one of those screens can

8
00:00:27,725 --> 00:00:30,725
show live, realtime data from your production console.

9
00:00:31,025 --> 00:00:33,275
Session status, countdowns, the current speaker,

10
00:00:33,575 --> 00:00:37,700
your sponsor reel — all updating automatically the moment anything changes.

11
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:41,750
And setting it up takes about two minutes per screen.

12
00:00:42,050 --> 00:00:44,050
Let's do it.

13
00:00:44,350 --> 00:00:47,350
The signage system in CueDeck has two parts.

14
00:00:47,650 --> 00:00:51,400
The first part is the Signage panel inside the production

15
00:00:51,700 --> 00:00:54,700
console — that's where the director configures displays,

16
00:00:54,1000 --> 00:00:57,250
sets their modes, and manages everything.

17
00:00:57,550 --> 00:01:00,925
You can see it here in the left sidebar.

18
00:01:01,225 --> 00:01:03,475
It's only visible to directors and

19
00:01:03,775 --> 00:01:06,025
to operators assigned the Signage role.

20
00:01:06,325 --> 00:01:09,325
The second part is the display page —

21
00:01:09,625 --> 00:01:13,375
that's `cuedeck-display.html`, or the `/display` path if you're on `app.cuedeck.io`.

22
00:01:13,675 --> 00:01:18,550
This is the page you open on the physical screens around your venue.

23
00:01:18,850 --> 00:01:21,850
It connects to Supabase in real time and

24
00:01:22,150 --> 00:01:25,150
renders whatever mode you've configured for that display.

25
00:01:25,450 --> 00:01:29,575
Each display in the system is a row in the database.

26
00:01:29,875 --> 00:01:32,125
It has a name, a zone,

27
00:01:32,425 --> 00:01:35,050
a content mode, and a unique URL.

28
00:01:35,350 --> 00:01:38,350
You open that URL on any screen —

29
00:01:38,650 --> 00:01:40,900
a browser tab in kiosk mode,

30
00:01:41,200 --> 00:01:43,450
a Raspberry Pi, a signage player,

31
00:01:43,750 --> 00:01:45,1000
anything with a modern browser —

32
00:01:46,300 --> 00:01:50,050
and it stays live for the duration of the event.

33
00:01:50,350 --> 00:01:54,100
In the director console, scroll down the left sidebar and

34
00:01:54,400 --> 00:01:56,400
you'll find the Signage section.

35
00:01:56,700 --> 00:02:00,450
If you don't see it, make sure you're logged in

36
00:02:00,750 --> 00:02:03,750
as a director — signage configuration is director-only.

37
00:02:04,050 --> 00:02:08,175
The panel shows you all the displays registered to this event.

38
00:02:08,475 --> 00:02:11,850
Each card has a name, a zone type —

39
00:02:12,150 --> 00:02:15,150
like 'lobby' or 'stage' — the content mode,

40
00:02:15,450 --> 00:02:18,075
the orientation, and a coloured dot that

41
00:02:18,375 --> 00:02:21,375
tells you whether the display is currently online.

42
00:02:21,675 --> 00:02:25,425
A green dot means the display page pinged the server

43
00:02:25,725 --> 00:02:27,725
within the last sixty seconds.

44
00:02:28,025 --> 00:02:31,025
Grey means it hasn't been seen recently —

45
00:02:31,325 --> 00:02:33,575
either the screen is off, or

46
00:02:33,875 --> 00:02:36,500
no one has opened that URL yet.

47
00:02:36,800 --> 00:02:40,550
That's useful context when you're setting up on the day:

48
00:02:40,850 --> 00:02:43,475
you can glance at the panel and

49
00:02:43,775 --> 00:02:46,400
know which screens are up and running.

50
00:02:46,700 --> 00:02:48,700
Let's add a display.

51
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:52,375
Click the plus button in the signage panel header.

52
00:02:52,675 --> 00:02:55,300
A modal opens — this is where

53
00:02:55,600 --> 00:02:57,850
you configure everything about one screen.

54
00:02:58,150 --> 00:03:00,150
First, give it a name.

55
00:03:00,450 --> 00:03:04,200
Something descriptive like 'Main Lobby Left' or 'Stage Left Monitor'.

56
00:03:04,500 --> 00:03:08,250
This is just for your reference in the panel —

57
00:03:08,550 --> 00:03:10,800
the physical screen doesn't show it.

58
00:03:11,100 --> 00:03:14,100
Zone type is the physical location category —

59
00:03:14,400 --> 00:03:16,400
lobby, stage, corridor, registration.

60
00:03:16,700 --> 00:03:19,325
This is also for your own organisation;

61
00:03:19,625 --> 00:03:23,000
it groups the cards in the panel by zone.

62
00:03:23,300 --> 00:03:25,300
Orientation: landscape or portrait.

63
00:03:25,600 --> 00:03:29,725
This tells the display page how to lay out the content.

64
00:03:30,025 --> 00:03:33,775
A portrait display — say, a vertical screen mounted in

65
00:03:34,075 --> 00:03:38,575
a column — will get a layout optimised for that aspect ratio.

66
00:03:38,875 --> 00:03:41,500
Content mode is the most important setting.

67
00:03:41,800 --> 00:03:44,425
This is what the screen actually shows.

68
00:03:44,725 --> 00:03:48,475
We'll cover all eleven modes in detail in the next

69
00:03:48,775 --> 00:03:51,775
episode, but for now I'll pick 'schedule' —

70
00:03:52,075 --> 00:03:56,575
that's the full programme list with live status badges on each session.

71
00:03:56,875 --> 00:03:58,875
Then there's the Room filter.

72
00:03:59,175 --> 00:04:02,925
If you only want this display to show sessions from

73
00:04:03,225 --> 00:04:06,225
a specific room — say, Hall A —

74
00:04:06,525 --> 00:04:08,525
you can set that here.

75
00:04:08,825 --> 00:04:12,200
Leave it blank and the display shows all sessions.

76
00:04:12,500 --> 00:04:14,500
Hit Save.

77
00:04:14,800 --> 00:04:17,800
The display card appears in the panel immediately.

78
00:04:18,100 --> 00:04:21,850
It starts grey because no one has opened the display

79
00:04:22,150 --> 00:04:25,525
URL yet — we'll fix that in a moment.

80
00:04:25,825 --> 00:04:29,575
Each display card has an Open button and a URL.

81
00:04:29,875 --> 00:04:33,625
Click Open and it launches the display page in a

82
00:04:33,925 --> 00:04:36,550
new tab, pre-loaded with this display's ID.

83
00:04:36,850 --> 00:04:39,850
The URL looks something like this — `app.cuedeck.io/display?id=abc123`.

84
00:04:40,150 --> 00:04:43,900
That `id` parameter is what ties this browser window to

85
00:04:44,200 --> 00:04:46,825
this specific display configuration in the database.

86
00:04:47,125 --> 00:04:50,875
Whatever you change in the signage panel for this display,

87
00:04:51,175 --> 00:04:54,925
that URL will reflect it, in real time, without refreshing.

88
00:04:55,225 --> 00:04:57,475
In practice: you copy this URL,

89
00:04:57,775 --> 00:05:02,275
paste it into the browser on the physical screen, and hit full-screen.

90
00:05:02,575 --> 00:05:04,575
That's your setup.

91
00:05:04,875 --> 00:05:06,875
The screen is now live.

92
00:05:07,175 --> 00:05:10,175
There it is — a full-screen schedule view,

93
00:05:10,475 --> 00:05:15,350
dark background, showing all the sessions for today's event with their live status.

94
00:05:15,650 --> 00:05:19,400
Any session that goes LIVE right now will light up

95
00:05:19,700 --> 00:05:22,700
with the live badge on this screen instantly.

96
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:27,125
Now let's talk about one of the more powerful features: sequences.

97
00:05:27,425 --> 00:05:30,050
Instead of showing a single mode forever,

98
00:05:30,350 --> 00:05:34,100
a display can cycle through multiple modes on a timer.

99
00:05:34,400 --> 00:05:37,400
This is perfect for a lobby screen —

100
00:05:37,700 --> 00:05:40,325
sponsors for twenty seconds, then the schedule,

101
00:05:40,625 --> 00:05:43,250
then the countdown to the next session,

102
00:05:43,550 --> 00:05:45,550
then back to sponsors.

103
00:05:45,850 --> 00:05:49,600
Scroll down in the display modal to the Sequence section.

104
00:05:49,900 --> 00:05:51,900
Click Add Slide.

105
00:05:52,200 --> 00:05:55,575
Each slide has two settings: the mode to show,

106
00:05:55,875 --> 00:05:59,250
and the number of seconds to show it for.

107
00:05:59,550 --> 00:06:02,550
I'll add three slides: sponsors for twenty seconds,

108
00:06:02,850 --> 00:06:05,475
schedule for thirty, and countdown for fifteen.

109
00:06:05,775 --> 00:06:09,150
You can add as many slides as you like.

110
00:06:09,450 --> 00:06:12,450
Drag to reorder them if you need to.

111
00:06:12,750 --> 00:06:14,750
Now hit Save.

112
00:06:15,050 --> 00:06:18,425
The display will begin cycling through these modes automatically.

113
00:06:18,725 --> 00:06:22,475
There's no reload — the display page reads the sequence

114
00:06:22,775 --> 00:06:26,525
from the database and starts the rotation as soon as

115
00:06:26,825 --> 00:06:28,825
it detects the change.

116
00:06:29,125 --> 00:06:33,625
There's one more setting worth knowing before we move on: scroll style.

117
00:06:33,925 --> 00:06:36,550
For modes that show a list —

118
00:06:36,850 --> 00:06:39,100
like schedule, timeline, or agenda —

119
00:06:39,400 --> 00:06:43,150
you can choose how the display handles content that's too

120
00:06:43,450 --> 00:06:46,075
long to fit on screen at once.

121
00:06:46,375 --> 00:06:48,625
'Scroll' does a continuous slow auto-scroll,

122
00:06:48,925 --> 00:06:51,175
looping back to the top when

123
00:06:51,475 --> 00:06:53,475
it reaches the bottom.

124
00:06:53,775 --> 00:06:56,775
This looks great on a lobby display that

125
00:06:57,075 --> 00:06:59,325
people glance at while walking past.

126
00:06:59,625 --> 00:07:02,625
'Paginate' instead shows a full page of sessions,

127
00:07:02,925 --> 00:07:05,550
holds for a set number of seconds,

128
00:07:05,850 --> 00:07:08,100
then cuts to the next page.

129
00:07:08,400 --> 00:07:12,150
The seconds-per-page field appears when you select this option —

130
00:07:12,450 --> 00:07:14,450
the default is ten seconds.

131
00:07:14,750 --> 00:07:18,500
Paginate is better for a seated audience who needs to

132
00:07:18,800 --> 00:07:21,050
read the full session titles carefully.

133
00:07:21,350 --> 00:07:23,600
Scroll is better for passing traffic.

134
00:07:23,900 --> 00:07:28,400
One last thing: you don't have to run the signage panel yourself.

135
00:07:28,700 --> 00:07:32,075
If your venue has a dedicated AV operator or

136
00:07:32,375 --> 00:07:36,125
a signage technician, you can assign them the Signage role

137
00:07:36,425 --> 00:07:38,425
in the Operators panel.

138
00:07:38,725 --> 00:07:42,475
The Signage role gives that person access to the signage

139
00:07:42,775 --> 00:07:46,150
panel and the context panel's global override buttons —

140
00:07:46,450 --> 00:07:49,450
things like putting all screens into break mode,

141
00:07:49,750 --> 00:07:54,625
triggering a speaker recall, or swapping to the sponsor reel with one click.

142
00:07:54,925 --> 00:07:59,425
They can manage all the physical displays without ever touching session controls.

143
00:07:59,725 --> 00:08:03,100
We'll see those global override buttons in action when

144
00:08:03,400 --> 00:08:06,025
we get to the display modes episode.

145
00:08:06,325 --> 00:08:10,075
So in about five minutes we went from nothing to

146
00:08:10,375 --> 00:08:12,375
a live signage system.

147
00:08:12,675 --> 00:08:15,300
We added a display, got its URL,

148
00:08:15,600 --> 00:08:17,850
opened it on a second screen,

149
00:08:18,150 --> 00:08:21,150
configured a sequence, and set up scroll behaviour.

150
00:08:21,450 --> 00:08:25,200
The key things to remember: every display has a unique

151
00:08:25,500 --> 00:08:27,750
URL tied to its database ID.

152
00:08:28,050 --> 00:08:32,925
Whatever you change in the signage panel updates the display in real time.

153
00:08:33,225 --> 00:08:36,975
And sequences let you rotate through multiple modes so one

154
00:08:37,275 --> 00:08:39,900
screen can do the work of three.

155
00:08:40,200 --> 00:08:43,950
In the next episode, we're doing a full tour of

156
00:08:44,250 --> 00:08:46,500
all eleven signage display modes —

157
00:08:46,800 --> 00:08:49,050
what each one looks like, when

158
00:08:49,350 --> 00:08:53,850
to use it, and how they adapt to your live event data.

159
00:08:54,150 --> 00:08:56,150
See you there.
